Modeling and prediction for movies

#Load Data
load("movies.Rdata")

Part 1: Data

The movies dataset is made up of 651 randomly sampled movies produced and released before 2016 from Rotten Tomatoes and IMBD. Since random sampling was used to collect the data, the results can be generalised to movies produced and released between 1970 and 2016.

However, only correlational statements and conclusions can be made as this is an observational study and the data collection involved no random assignment to perform an experiment.

The data in the dataset comes from Rotten Tomatoes and IMDB, both of which are sites that volunteers contribute to. It’s possible that only people with strong opinions about a movie and movie enthusiasts contribute to the two sites. Hence, the data itself might include convenience and response biases that makes the data different from that of the actual population.

Part 2: Research question

What aspects of a movie are associated closely with the audience score on Rotten Tomatoes?

We’ll look at the different variables of a movie such as genre, runtime etc. to investigate to what extent they can predict audience_score.

It will be interesting to see what kind of influence different factors have on the audience’s scores.

Part 3: Exploratory data analysis

Data Pre-processing

We will not be using all the variables given in the dataset as some of them are not quite relevant for our purposes. We will get rid of the title, studio, director, actor1 - actor5, mpaa_rating, imdb_url and rt_url since these are of no statistical relevance. We will also get rid of the release dates for DVD to simplify the analysis.

#Extract data
moviedata <- movies %>% select(-title, -mpaa_rating, -studio,
                               -thtr_rel_day:-dvd_rel_day, -imdb_num_votes, -director:-rt_url)

#Get rid of the observations with NA
moviedata <- moviedata %>% na.omit()

Exploration of the data

For our research question we are ultimately interested in predicting the audience reception of a movie. Hence our response variables would be audience_score. Let’s look at a histogram of this variable to get a sense of the distribution shape.

#Histogram of Rotten Tomatoes Audience Scores
ggplot(moviedata, aes(x = audience_score)) + geom_histogram(binwidth = 2) + 
  labs(title ="Histogram of Rotten Tomatoes Scores" ,x = "Audience Score")

The plot shows left skewness, with the bulk of the responses in the right section of the plot.

Let’s now look at pairwise relationships of some of the numerical variables we want to include in our model later on.

#Pairwise Plots
ggpairs(moviedata, columns = c(3,6,8,10))

From the pairwise scatterplots and the calculated correlation coefficients, we see that the correlations between the runtime and other variables are minimal. However, imdb_rating, critics_score and audience_score show stronger correlations with each other.

Part 4: Modeling

In this section, we will be building a multiple linear regression model with audience_score as the response variable. The full model for audience score will include title type, genre, runtime, release year and month, critics score,imdb rating, best picture nomination and win, best actor/actress/director Oscar wins and top whether the movie made it into the 200 box office list.

We are excluding title, studio, director, actor1 - actor5, mpaa_rating, imdb_url and rt_url since these are of no statistical relevance. We also excluded theatre release day, and DVD release dates since these are not so relevant to our analyses. We will also remove audience_rating since it is just a consolidated version of the audience_score and it doesn’t make sense to predict one when you have the other.

Model Fit

We’ll be using backward elimination with adjusted R squared as the model selection method since it lets us drop variables one by one until we reach an adequately parsimonious model. We’ll use adjusted R-squared instead of p-value because unlike p-value, adjusted R-squared gives us an idea of the overall model fit and not just for each individual variable. First let’s fit the model for audience_score.

#Fit Full Model
audience <- moviedata %>% select(-audience_rating)
full <- lm(audience_score ~ ., data = audience)
summary(full)

We see that the adjusted R-squared is 76.95%. We will now perform backward selection using the step function with direction ‘backward’ to check if a more parsimonious model is possible.

#Backward elimination for Rotten Tomatoes audience score
final <- step(full, direction = "backward", trace = 0)
summary(final)

From the output, we see that the regression model with only the genre, runtime, theatre release year and month, imdb rating, critics rating, best pic nomination and best actress winning is a parsimonious model with an adjusted R-squared value of 77.11%.

It is also seen that the imdb rating, genre of Animation and nomination for best picture Oscar make the most positive impact on the response variable. For instance, an increase of 1 point of imdb_rating increases the audience_score by 14.98 on average. On the other hand, movies of the genres Mystery & Suspense and Horror have on average an audience score of 5.5 less than the reference level genre ‘Action and Adventure’.

Model Diagnostics

Linear relationships between predictor and response
We’ll first check for linear relationships between numerical predictor variables and the response variable audience_score by plotting residuals against each predictor.

#Residuals against Run Time
plot(final$residuals ~ audience$runtime, main = "Residuals Against Run Time", ylab = "Residuals",
     xlab = "RunTime")

#Residuals against Release Year
plot(final$residuals ~ audience$thtr_rel_year, main = "Residuals Against Release Year", 
     ylab = "Residuals", xlab = "Release Year")

#Residuals against Release Month
plot(final$residuals ~ audience$thtr_rel_month, main = "Residuals Against Release Month", 
     ylab = "Residuals", xlab = "Release Month")

#Residuals against IMDB Rating
plot(final$residuals ~ audience$imdb_rating, main = "Residuals Against IMDB Rating", 
     ylab = "Residuals", xlab = "IMDB Rating")

For runtime and release month, we see random scatter around 0. For theatre release year, some of the movies in the later years have higher residuals. For imdb_rating, we see higher residulas for ratings lower than 4. This could restrict the generalizability of the model in those ranges but in general, this condition is fairly satisfied.

Nearly Normal Residuals
We want to see random scatter of residuals around 0. This can be checked using a histogram of residuals or a normal probability plot of residuals. We’ll do both here.

#Histogram of Residuals
hist(final$residuals, main = "Histogram of Residuals", xlab = "Residuals")

#Normal Probability Plot of Residuals
qqnorm(final$residuals)
qqline(final$residuals)

Even though the histogram shows a slight skew, it is nearly normal. The QQ plot is a fairly straight line except for the end values. Hence this condition is satisfied.

Constant variability of residuals
We can check for constant variability of residuals by plotting residuals vs the predicted response values.

#Residuals Vs Fitted 
plot(final$residuals ~ final$fitted, main = "Residuals Vs Predicted Values", 
     xlab = "Fitted Values", ylab = "Residuals")

The plot is generally homoscedastic. We do see less random scatter at higher fitted values. This suggests that the model would be less accurate when predicting higher values. Otherwise, this condition is satisfied.

Independence of residuals
We can check to see if there is any time series structure embedded in the dataset by plotting residuals against theatre release year.

#Residuals against Release Year
plot(final$residuals ~ audience$thtr_rel_year, xlab = "Release Year", 
     ylab ="Residuals", main = "Residuals against Release Year")

The scatter seems completely random except for a couple of outliers. Hence, from this plot and the random sampling used, we can see that this condition is also satisfied.

Part 5: Prediction

We are now ready to predict the audience score for a movie that is not included in our dataset. The movie to be predicted is “The Little Prince”, released in August 2016. We have extracted the runtime, release year and month, IMDB rating and critics rating from Rotten Tomatoes and IMDB. We’ll now predict a 95% prediction interval with our model. This means that if repeated samples were taken, then 95% of the samples that contain the true parameter would be between our 95% prediction interval.

predict_movie <- data.frame(genre="Drama",runtime=106, thtr_rel_year = 2016,
                            thtr_rel_month = 8, imdb_rating = 7.7, 
                            critics_rating= "Certified Fresh",
                            best_pic_nom = "no", best_actress_win = "no")
predict(final, predict_movie, interval = "predict")
##        fit      lwr      upr
## 1 82.30032 63.15576 101.4449

The 95% prediction interval is (64.15, 101.44) with the mean value 82.30%. The actual rating that “The Little Prince” received on Rotten Tomatoes was 84%. Our prediction seems to be working alright.

Part 6: Conclusion

We have now built a multiple linear regression model that predicts the audience scores on Rotten Tomatoes using a few factors namely, the genre, runtime, release year and month, ratings on IMDB, critics ratings, whether it was nominated for Oscar for best picture and whether it has an actress who won an Oscar before. It is seen that not all of these factors are intrinsic to the movie but some are extrinsic as well. This is a limitation because we won’t be able to predict the audience scores with this model before the movie comes out since we won’t know IMDB ratings, critics ratings and whether it will be nominated for Oscar until after the movie is released. So although it’s pretty accurate, it might not be as accurate if the extrinsic variables were dropped from the model. Another limitation is that the predictions only represent the audience scores on Rotten Tomatoes and may not exactly reflect the actual population’s opinion.
